        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Configuration:
We request any configuration capable of delivering angular resolution better than 1''. The two bright and compact lensed images of the blazar are separated by 1'', with well known relative positions from VLBI observations. Hence, we will self-calibrate the data and perform visibility fitting to extract the spectra toward each image. The signal-to-noise ratio will be sufficient for the visibility fitting to separate both blazar images, even on a spectral channel basis.

Spectral setup:
We request four basebands of 1.875 GHz wide to cover the CF+ 2-1 line and the full available bandwidth to search for other potential absorption lines. We adopt a velocity resolution of ~3 km/s, sufficient to resolve the line. This leads to high data rate, but will provide us with the detection of multiple species in addition to our targeted ones. In particular there are strong absorption of HCO+ and HNC (J=2-1) in the band.

Requested sensitivity:
We estimate the flux density F(SW) and F(NE) of the two blazar images as F = F0 (nu/nu0)^-alpha. We take alpha=0.7, F0(NE)=1.7 Jy at 100 GHz, and a magnification ratio F(NE)/F(SW)=1.5. This gives F(SW)=1.07 Jy for the SW image, the one with the deepest absorption. We target a sensitivity of 1% of the continuum level (ie tau=0.01) at 3 sigma toward the SW image, that is 3.6 mJy, for a velocity resolution of ~3 km/s, given by the finest spectral resolution.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
